level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure (customer receives first draft instead of regenerated response) is an orchestration/routing bug that only surfaces when the tone-check output is wired to the response-selection logic — not visible inside any single function. REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed; all failure modes are in in-process conditional branching. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the LLM to return 'formal_draft' and 'casual_response' plus mocking the tone checker to return 'too_formal' is sufficient — the routing bug is deterministic and fully observable with mocks. LLM-DEP: This behavior is about WHICH response is served (routing correctness), not about the QUALITY of either response. The classification and generation results can be fully controlled with mocks to put the pipeline on the regeneration path. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic was considered; rejected because 'customer never sees the rejected draft' is a deterministic routing invariant — mocking does not hide this failure.","test_description":"Wire all components together with a real (non-mocked) orchestration layer. Mock the first LLM call to return a detectably over-formal response string. Mock the tone-check classifier to return 'too_formal'. Mock the second LLM call to return a clearly different casual response string. Invoke the full handler and assert: (a) the value returned to the caller equals the second (casual) response, and (b) the first (formal) draft string does not appear anywhere in the customer-facing output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.16,"Workflow":0.1}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence"